1
00:00:00,100 --> 00:00:08,517
What do desalination membranes, methane catalysts, safer refrigerants, lithium recovery, P-fass cleanup, clean-air catalysts, and low-carbon cement have in common?

2
00:00:08,467 --> 00:00:10,895
Weirdly, the same atomic blind spot.

3
00:00:10,895 --> 00:00:13,500
The materials bottleneck is not climate-specific.

4
00:00:13,500 --> 00:00:15,298
It is coordination-specific.

5
00:00:15,298 --> 00:00:20,330
Universal machine-learning potentials learn tidy bulk crystals, where atoms have lots of regular neighbors.

6
00:00:20,330 --> 00:00:26,612
But useful chemistry happens at pores, surfaces, vacancies, and transition states—where atoms have fewer neighbors.

7
00:00:26,612 --> 00:00:31,000
Right there, these models can soften the energy landscape by 15 to 60 percent.

8
00:00:31,000 --> 00:00:32,766
That is not harmless noise.

9
00:00:32,766 --> 00:00:39,177
A softened barrier can make the wrong membrane look selective, the wrong catalyst look fast, or an unmakeable cement phase look stable.

10
00:00:39,177 --> 00:00:44,637
Across millions of candidates, tiny systematic errors flip rankings—and experiments chase false winners.

11
00:00:44,637 --> 00:00:48,274
The stakes are huge: water scarcity affects roughly two billion people.

12
00:00:48,274 --> 00:00:50,605
Air pollution kills millions every year.

13
00:00:50,605 --> 00:00:53,354
Methane drives about 30 percent of current warming.

14
00:00:53,354 --> 00:00:57,185
Clean-energy mineral demand could rise four- to six-fold by 2040.

15
00:00:57,185 --> 00:01:01,612
And cement alone produces roughly 2.8 gigatonnes of carbon dioxide annually.

16
00:01:01,612 --> 00:01:05,048
Lupine’s response starts with the useful part: the error has a shape.

17
00:01:05,048 --> 00:01:08,117
Three measured observables anchor an environment error field.

18
00:01:08,117 --> 00:01:14,991
Bulk coordination is fixed at zero error, and a constrained curve predicts corrections for under-coordinated environments the field never directly saw.

19
00:01:14,991 --> 00:01:22,556
Add that field at runtime, and simulations follow corrected energies and analytic forces—still about one hundred thousand times faster than quantum chemistry.

20
00:01:22,556 --> 00:01:28,556
In blind tests across 36 model-material pairs, predicted corrections correlated at zero point nine oh six.

21
00:01:28,556 --> 00:01:33,935
Then 77 build-locked Lean 4 theorems mark what is supported, out of domain, or synthesis-dependent.

22
00:01:33,935 --> 00:01:35,774
So this is bigger than carbon.

23
00:01:35,774 --> 00:01:42,862
One correction-and-verification layer can improve discovery across water, air, methane, refrigerants, minerals, P-fass, and cement.

24
00:01:42,862 --> 00:01:44,120
Measure the error.

25
00:01:44,120 --> 00:01:45,572
Correct the physics.

26
00:01:45,572 --> 00:01:46,895
Prove the boundary.

27
00:01:46,895 --> 00:01:49,862
Then send experiments the candidates actually worth making.

